Abstract

Introduction.

Sepsis is a clinical syndrome that defines human body reaction to infection by microbial pathogens. Delay in sepsis diagnosis and inappropriate treatment are associated with high mortality. Blood cell count is a major baseline laboratory investigation for a suspected case of sepsis. Multiple parameters are analyzed and reported in the complete blood cell count analysis that estimate human body immune response to microbial infection. Statistical analysis of blood cell changes in sepsis may reveal underlying structure that may assist in interpretation of initial blood cell laboratory results of suspected sepsis case and lead to improved diagnosis and better outcome of sepsis.

Methodology:

Data from medical information mart for intensive care (MIMIC IV) database from Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center was used to analyze the correlation of various blood cell components in sepsis. Statistical analysis was done using R software

Results:

Factor analysis was performed on 83 individuals, described by fourteen (14) variables. Six components had eigen values greater than 1.0 with cumulative variance of 85.5%. Hematocrit, hemoglobin and red blood cells loaded uniquely in the first factor. Neutrophils, lymphocytes and monocytes loaded highly in the second factor. MCV and MCH loaded well in the third factor.

Discussion and Conclusion;

Blood cell changes in sepsis occur mainly in three patterns described by hemoglobin changes, inflammatory changes and morphological changes. These categories may be used to interpret the initial blood cell results of a suspected case of sepsis.

13. Scoop laboratory value related to each item_id, loop and merge into data frame by subject_id.

data0 <- labs_sepsis |> select(subject_id) |> distinct()

for (i in bloodcell_itemid$itemid) {
    
    data01<- labs_sepsis |>  filter(itemid==i) |>
      group_by (subject_id) |>
      arrange(subject_id) |> 
      arrange (charttime) |> filter(row_number()==1) |>
      select(subject_id, value) |> 
      merge(data0,data01,by.x = "subject_id" ,by.y = "subject_id", all=TRUE, sort = TRUE) 
    
    
      data0 <- data01
}

  data02<- data01[!duplicated(as.list(data01))] 
  names(data02) [-1] <- rev(bloodcell_itemid$label)

22. Multivariate outlier assesment

#mahalanobis(sepsis_data5,colMeans(sepsis_data5), cov(sepsis_data5))

sepsis_mahalanobis <- sepsis_data5 |>
  mutate(mahalanob_value =mahalanobis(sepsis_data5,colMeans(sepsis_data5), cov(sepsis_data5)))

24. Category of white cell changes in sepsis.

whitecell_categories <- sepsis_data6 |>
  mutate(whitecell_categ= case_when(white_blood_cells < 4.0 ~"Low", white_blood_cells > 11.0 ~"High", white_blood_cells >=  4.0 ~"Normal"),.before = white_blood_cells)

ggplot(aes(whitecell_categ)) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(fill = whitecell_categ))
